{"cursor":"3647","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Chembox\n| Watchedfields= changed ImageFile = Hyponitrous acid trans.svg ImageName =\n| Tautomer wireframe models of hyponitrous acid PIN = Diazenediol SystematicName\n| = N-(Hydroxyimino)hydroxylamine OtherNames = Hyponitrous acid dimer Section1 =\n| {{Chembox Identifiers CASNo = 14448-38-5 PubChem = 61744 PubChem_Ref =\n| ChemSpiderID = 55636 ChemSpiderID_Ref = KEGG = C01818 ChEBI = 14428 SMILES =\n| ON=NO InChI = 1S/H2N2O/c3-1-2-4/h(H,1,4)(H,2,3) InChIKey = NFMHSPWHNQRFNR-UHFFFAOYSA-\n| N Gmelin = 141300 3DMet = B00354}} Section2 = {{Chembox Properties Formula =\n| H 2N 2O 2 MolarMass = 62.0282 g/mol Appearance =\n| white crystals Density = MeltingPt = BoilingPt = Solubility = }} Section3 =\n| {{Chembox Hazards MainHazards = explosive when dry FlashPt = Autoignition = }}\n}} 'Hyponitrous acid' is the chemical compound\nH 2N 2O 2. This can be formulated as HON=NOH and\nis an isomer of nitramide, (H 2NâNO2). It forms white crystals that\nare explosive when dry. Egon Wiberg, Arnold\nFrederick Holleman (2001) Inorganic Chemistry, Elsevier ISBN 0-12-352651-5\n\nHyponitrous acid is a weak acid (pk 1 = 7.21, pK 2= 11.54)\nin aqueous solution and decomposes to N 2O and water with a half-life\nof 16 days at 25Â°C at pH 1-3.\n\n:H 2N 2O 2→ H 2O + N 2O\n\nAs this reaction is not reversible, N 2O should not be considered as\nthe anhydride of H 2N 2O 2.\n\nHyponitrous acid forms two series of salts, the \"acid hyponitrites\" containing\n[HON=N] â anion and hyponitrites containing the [ON=NO] 2â\nanion.\n\nThe hyponitrite ion [ON=NO] 2â can be prepared in aqueous solution by\ntwo methods. One method uses organic nitrites to synthesize the sodium salt: {{cite book\n| title = Inorganic Chemistry, 3rd Edition chapter = Chapter 15: The group 15\n| elements author1 = Catherine E. Housecroft author2 = Alan G. Sharpe publisher\n| = Pearson year = 2008 isbn = 978-0-13-175553-6 page = 468\n}}\n\n: RONO + NH 2OH + 2 EtONa â Na 2N 2O 2 +\n: ROH + 2 EtOH\n\nAnother method is by the reduction of sodium nitrite to give the silver\nsalt:\n\n:2 NaNO 2 + 4 NaHg + 2 H 2O + 2 AgNO 3 â\n:Ag 2N 2O 2 + 2 NaNO 3 + 4 NaOH + 4 Hg\n\nAddition of Ag +(aq) ions precipitates\nAg 2N 2O 2 from solution. The free acid is then\nprepared from silver hyponitrite and anhydrous HCl in ether:\n\n:Ag 2N 2O 2 + 2 HCl â\nH 2N 2O 2 + 2 AgCl\n\nThere are two possible structures of hyponitrous acid, trans and cis, and the\nsolid Na 2N 2O 2â¢5H 2O is confirmed to\nbe the trans form. Spectroscopic data also indicate a\ntrans configuration of the free acid. The cis-form can be prepared as the sodium\nsalt Na 2N 2O 2 by heating Na 2O with\ngaseous N 2O.\n","linknr":206,"url":"Hyponitrous_acid","recorded":1374783069,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hyponitrous_acid&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hyponitrous_acid&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Hyponitrous_acid_trans.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Hyponitrous_acid_trans.svg/200px-Hyponitrous_acid_trans.svg.png","/wiki/Preferred_IUPAC_name","/wiki/IUPAC_nomenclature","/wiki/CAS_registry_number","http://www.commonchemistry.org/ChemicalDetail.aspx?